Anonymous Tue 29 Jun 2021 02:44:45 No.39786674 Report
Quoted By:
>>39785396
>identify the speaker after every change
The way I was taught, and have seen pushed in mainstream publishing, is that it should be unambiguous.
So for two characters...
Cold open to a chapter
Alice <- attribute by any method
Bob <- attribute, even though it should be clear without we do it anyway
Alice <- non-attributed
Bob
Alice
Alice and Bob move about the room
Alice continues <- attribute using action tag at the beginning of the paragraph, so that it flows from the previous one

The funny thing is that writefags here that prefer attributing via action get beat up a lot, yet the second bit of advice I got on dialogue after learning to attribute was to cut the number of "saids" to a third or quarter.
Part of this was because I'm a dialogue first writer, and it makes a hell of a lot of sense as a reader. It forces the writer to connect what is being said to the actions or posture of the characters and allows one to cut a lot of cruft.

You have more of a point with three or more characters, but again with clever use of action and dialogue cues a writer can leave out attributions to control the pace.
As for Kaktus, I have no problem following HATS^5. While I would have broken the paragraphs in the first chapter to unjumble Missy's dialogue and Leo's reactive thoughts, I've used the exact same technique in first person. I've seen it used far more professionally in first, but it works in third like a camera dollying back a bit from the MC.
Now if you really want to dip deeper, I've noticed differences between Brit & American writers. It's not confusing as long as there's consistency.

Last point to you - people should read the attribution rules, but if you can't follow then slow the hell down. That's a good sign you missed more than you think.

Not >>39785396

How I would have written that, option one
“Sure, suuuuuuure.” Missy nodded slowly. “Will do, buddy. You got it.”
Leo hesitantly sat down on the side of the bed, taking up as much of the edge as he could.
Missy fluffed the pillow in her hands and asked, “So how about some TV before bed?”

How I would have written that, option two
“Sure, suuuuuuure,” Missy said as she nodded slowly. “Will do, buddy. You got it.” She stayed put at Leo hesitantly sat down on the side of the bed, taking up as much of the edge as he could and added, “So how about some TV before bed?”

How I break dialogue is determined more by when the character completes a thought. So for me the second option is better as it doesn't break the paragraph, but keeps the camera focus on Missy the whole time.
Now if the desired effect was to create a quick camera flick between the characters, then the first works better.
It all boils down to the writer controlling the flow how they want.
